Summary.Unnamed: 1: Source: SPI M Preliminary Long Term Scenarios week commencing 9 October
These estimates represent indicative scenarios and are not precise predictions of what is going to happen
They are part of preparatory work to support planning for the winter period and the development of a new iteration of the government’s reasonable worst case scenario.
This modelling show a range of possibilities as to what might happen in such a worst case scenario under the pessimistic assumptions and no further policy changes as of 9 October.
Please see accompanying documentation ("SPI-M preparatory analysis long term scenarios") for further details about this work and how it is used.
Note the following details relating to these scenarios:
1. The data includes the median of each models estimates, as well as the upper and lower bound corresponding to the 95% and 5% quantile respectively.

Summary.Supporting data to accompany the Chief S: England - daily hospital admissions to date with SPI-M medium term projection for the next six weeks

Summary.Unnamed: 1: Source: Scientific Pandemic Influenza Group on Modelling (SPI-M)
These projections represent SPI-M-O’s best assessment of the potential trajectory of the epidemic over the next six weeks, based on current trends and data available up to 26th October.

The projections should not be interpreted as forecasts or predictions. They represent a scenario in which the trajectory of the epidemic continues to follow current trends and do not account for the impact of future policy or behaviour changes.
Past data on the number of deaths within 28 days of positive test and COVID-19 patients admitted to hospital in England is available on PHE's 'GOV.UK Coronavirus (COVID-19) in the UK' dashboard:
https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/
Please see accompanying documentation ("SPI-M-O medium term projections explainer") for further details about this work and how it is used.
Note the following details relating to these projections:

1. The delay between infection, developing symptoms, hospitalisation, and death means the projections cannot fully reflect changes in transmission which might have occurred over the past two to three weeks.
2. Separate projections are produced using different models and approaches. These individual projections are then combined to form a consensus projection.
3. The data includes the median of the consensus projection, as well as the upper and lower bound of the interquartile range.
Dataset used for chart included at tab "England hospital admissions"
